<p><b>Plotinus</b> (<a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">Greek</a>: <span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">Πλωτῖνος</span>) (ca. AD 204–270) was a major <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosopher</a> of the ancient world who is widely considered the founder of <a href="/wiki/Neoplatonism" title="Neoplatonism">Neoplatonism</a> (along with his teacher <a href="/wiki/Ammonius_Saccas" title="Ammonius Saccas">Ammonius Saccas</a>). Much of our biographical information about him comes from <a href="/wiki/Porphyry_(philosopher)" title="Porphyry (philosopher)">Porphyry</a>'s preface to his edition of Plotinus' <i><a href="/wiki/Enneads" title="Enneads">Enneads</a></i>. His <a href="/wiki/Metaphysics" title="Metaphysics">metaphysical</a> writings have inspired centuries of <a href="/wiki/Pagan" title="Pagan" class="mw-redirect">Pagan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Christian_philosophy" title="Christian philosophy">Christian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jewish_philosophy" title="Jewish philosophy">Jewish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Early_Islamic_philosophy" title="Early Islamic philosophy">Islamic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gnosticism" title="Gnosticism">Gnostic</a> metaphysicians and mystics.</p>
